.TH sasl_client_new 3SASL "27 Aug 2003" "SunOS 5.11" "Simple Authentication Security Layer Library Functions"
.SH NAME
sasl_client_new \- create a new client authentication object
.SH SYNOPSIS
.LP
.nf
\fBcc\fR [ \fIflag\fR .\|.\|. ] \fIfile\fR .\|.\|. \fB-lsasl\fR   [ \fIlibrary\fR .\|.\|. ]
#include <sasl/sasl.h>

\fBint\fR \fBsasl_client_new\fR(\fBconst char *\fIservice\fR, \fBconst char *\fIserverFQDN\fR,
     \fBconst char *\fIiplocalport\fR, \fBconst char *\fIipremoteport\fR,
     \fBconst sasl_callback_t *\fIprompt_supp\fR, \fBunsigned\fR \fIflags\fR,
     \fBsasl_conn_t **\fIpconn\fR);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
.LP
Use the \fBsasl_client_new()\fR interface to create a new SASL context.
This SASL context will be used for all SASL calls for one connection. The
context handles both authentication and the integrity and encryption layers
after authentication.
.SH PARAMETERS
.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIservice\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
The registered name of the service that uses SASL, usually the protocol
name, for example, IMAP.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIserverFQDN\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
The fully qualified domain name of the server, for example,
serverhost.cmu.edu.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIiplocalport\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
.sp
.LP
The IP and port of the local side of the connection, or \fINULL\fR. If
\fIiplocalport\fR is \fINULL\fR, mechanisms that require IP address
information are disabled. The \fIiplocalport\fR string must be in one of the
following formats:
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fBa.b.c.d:port\fR (IPv6)
.RE
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fB[e:f:g:h:i:j:k:l]:port\fR (IPv6)
.RE
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fB[e:f:g:h:i:j:a.b.c.d]:port\fR (IPv6)
.RE
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fBa.b.c.d;port\fR (IPv4)
.RE
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fBe:f:g:h:i:j:k:l;port\fR (IPv6)
.RE
.RS +4
.TP
.ie t \(bu
.el o
\fBe:f:g:h:i:j:a.b.c.d;port\fR (IPv6)
.RE
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIipremoteport\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
The IP and port of the remote side of the connection, or \fINULL\fR.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIprompt_supp\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
A list of the client interactions supported that are unique to this
connection. If this parameter is \fINULL\fR, the global callbacks specified
in \fBsasl_client_init\fR(3SASL) are used.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIflags\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
Usage flags. For clients, the flag \fBSASL_NEED_PROXY\fR is available.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fIpconn\fR
.ad
.RS 16n
.rt
The connection context allocated by the library. The \fIpconn\fR structure
is used for all future SASL calls for this connection.
.RE

.SH RETURN VALUES
.sp
.LP
\fBsasl_client_new()\fR returns an integer that corresponds to a SASL error
code.
.SH ERRORS
.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBSASL_OK\fR
.ad
.RS 17n
.rt
The call to \fBsasl_client_new()\fR was successful.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBSASL_NOMECH\fR
.ad
.RS 17n
.rt
No mechanishm meets the requested properties.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBSASL_BADPARAM\fR
.ad
.RS 17n
.rt
There is an error in the configuration file or passed parameters.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBSASL_NOMEM\fR
.ad
.RS 17n
.rt
There is not enough memory to complete the operation.
.RE

.sp
.LP
All other error codes indicate an error situation that must be handled, or
the authentication session should be quit. See \fBsasl_errors\fR(3SASL) for
information on SASL error codes.
.SH ATTRIBUTES
.sp
.LP
See \fBattributes\fR(5) for descriptions of the following attributes:
.sp

